1
00:00:01,820 --> 00:00:04,455
How does PCA work?

2
00:00:04,455 --> 00:00:09,215
If you have a dataset with
two features, x_1 and x_2.

3
00:00:09,215 --> 00:00:11,810
Initially, your
data is plotted or

4
00:00:11,810 --> 00:00:15,945
represented using
axes x_1 and x_2.

5
00:00:15,945 --> 00:00:17,985
But you want to replace

6
00:00:17,985 --> 00:00:20,670
these two features
with just one feature.

7
00:00:20,670 --> 00:00:23,025
How can you choose a new axis,

8
00:00:23,025 --> 00:00:24,735
let's call it the z-axis,

9
00:00:24,735 --> 00:00:28,740
that is somehow a good
feature for capturing,

10
00:00:28,740 --> 00:00:30,645
of representing the data?

11
00:00:30,645 --> 00:00:33,870
Let's take a look at
how PCA does this.

12
00:00:33,870 --> 00:00:38,805
Here's the data sets with
five training examples.

13
00:00:38,805 --> 00:00:42,630
Remember, this is an
unsupervised learning algorithm

14
00:00:42,630 --> 00:00:45,030
so we just have x_1 and x_2,

15
00:00:45,030 --> 00:00:48,030
there is no label y.

16
00:00:48,030 --> 00:00:52,670
An example here like this
may have coordinates x_1

17
00:00:52,670 --> 00:01:02,640
equals 10 and x_2 equals 8.

18
00:01:02,660 --> 00:01:06,980
If we don't want to
use the x_1, x_2 axes,

19
00:01:06,980 --> 00:01:11,240
how can we pick some
different axis with which to

20
00:01:11,240 --> 00:01:13,280
capture what's in
the data or with

21
00:01:13,280 --> 00:01:16,050
which to represent the data?

22
00:01:16,050 --> 00:01:18,240
One note on preprocessing,

23
00:01:18,240 --> 00:01:22,265
before applying the next few
steps of PCA the features

24
00:01:22,265 --> 00:01:24,170
should be first
normalized to have

25
00:01:24,170 --> 00:01:27,330
zero mean and I've
already done that here.

26
00:01:30,860 --> 00:01:33,435
If the features x_1 and

27
00:01:33,435 --> 00:01:36,120
x_2 take on very
different scales,

28
00:01:36,120 --> 00:01:39,650
for example, if you remember
our housing example,

29
00:01:39,650 --> 00:01:43,820
if x_1 was the size of
a house in square feet,

30
00:01:43,820 --> 00:01:46,890
and x_2 was the number
of bedrooms then

31
00:01:46,890 --> 00:01:50,540
x_1 could be 1,000 or
a couple of thousand,

32
00:01:50,540 --> 00:01:53,405
whereas x_2 is a small number.

33
00:01:53,405 --> 00:01:57,665
If the features take on
very different scales,

34
00:01:57,665 --> 00:02:00,110
then you will first
perform feature

35
00:02:00,110 --> 00:02:03,965
scaling before applying
the next few steps of PCA.

36
00:02:03,965 --> 00:02:06,470
Assuming the features have been

37
00:02:06,470 --> 00:02:08,465
normalized to have zero mean,

38
00:02:08,465 --> 00:02:09,770
so subtract the mean from

39
00:02:09,770 --> 00:02:12,710
each feature and
then maybe apply

40
00:02:12,710 --> 00:02:14,405
feature scaling as well

41
00:02:14,405 --> 00:02:17,270
so the ranges are
not too far apart.

42
00:02:17,270 --> 00:02:19,210
What does PCA do next?

43
00:02:19,210 --> 00:02:21,855
To examine what PCA does,

44
00:02:21,855 --> 00:02:24,960
let me remove the
x_1 and x_2 axes so

45
00:02:24,960 --> 00:02:28,475
that we're just left with
the five training examples.

46
00:02:28,475 --> 00:02:31,940
This dot here
represents the origin.

47
00:02:31,940 --> 00:02:35,360
The position of zero
on this plot still.

48
00:02:35,360 --> 00:02:38,390
What we have to do
now with PCA is,

49
00:02:38,390 --> 00:02:40,970
pick one axis instead

50
00:02:40,970 --> 00:02:43,310
of the two axes that
we had previously

51
00:02:43,310 --> 00:02:45,555
with which to capture

52
00:02:45,555 --> 00:02:48,560
what's important about
these five examples.

53
00:02:48,560 --> 00:02:54,110
If we were to choose this
axis to be our new z-axis,

54
00:02:54,110 --> 00:02:56,255
it's actually the
same as the x_1 axis

55
00:02:56,255 --> 00:02:58,215
just for this example.

56
00:02:58,215 --> 00:03:01,399
Then what we're saying is
that for this example,

57
00:03:01,399 --> 00:03:04,355
we're going to just
capture this value,

58
00:03:04,355 --> 00:03:06,935
this coordinate on the z-axis.

59
00:03:06,935 --> 00:03:08,434
For the second example,

60
00:03:08,434 --> 00:03:10,710
we're going to
capture this value,

61
00:03:10,710 --> 00:03:14,000
and then this will
capture this value,

62
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:18,025
and so on for all five examples.

63
00:03:18,025 --> 00:03:20,660
Another way of
saying this is that

64
00:03:20,660 --> 00:03:22,700
we're going to take
each of these examples

65
00:03:22,700 --> 00:03:27,510
and project it down to
a point on the z-axis.

66
00:03:27,510 --> 00:03:30,435
The word project refers to that

67
00:03:30,435 --> 00:03:33,410
you're taking this example
and bringing it to

68
00:03:33,410 --> 00:03:36,290
the z-axis using
this line segment

69
00:03:36,290 --> 00:03:39,050
that's at a 90-degree
angle to the z-axis.

70
00:03:39,050 --> 00:03:42,470
This little box here
is used to denote that

71
00:03:42,470 --> 00:03:46,480
this line segment is at
90 degrees to the z-axis.

72
00:03:46,480 --> 00:03:48,650
The term project
just means you're

73
00:03:48,650 --> 00:03:51,140
taking a point and finding

74
00:03:51,140 --> 00:03:53,735
this corresponding
point on the z-axis

75
00:03:53,735 --> 00:03:57,110
using this line segment
that's at 90 degrees.

76
00:03:57,110 --> 00:04:02,165
Picking this direction as a
z-axis is not a bad choice,

77
00:04:02,165 --> 00:04:04,475
but there's some
even better choices.

78
00:04:04,475 --> 00:04:07,040
This choice isn't
too bad because

79
00:04:07,040 --> 00:04:10,430
when you project your
examples onto the z-axis,

80
00:04:10,430 --> 00:04:14,285
you still capture quite a lot
of the spread of the data.

81
00:04:14,285 --> 00:04:16,865
These five points here,

82
00:04:16,865 --> 00:04:18,230
they're pretty spread apart

83
00:04:18,230 --> 00:04:19,550
so you're still
capturing a lot of

84
00:04:19,550 --> 00:04:21,710
the variation or a lot of

85
00:04:21,710 --> 00:04:24,235
the variance in the
original dataset.

86
00:04:24,235 --> 00:04:28,885
By that I mean these five
points are quite spread

87
00:04:28,885 --> 00:04:32,325
apart and so the variance

88
00:04:32,325 --> 00:04:35,120
or variation among
these five points,

89
00:04:35,120 --> 00:04:36,560
the projections of the data onto

90
00:04:36,560 --> 00:04:39,590
the z-axis is decently large.

91
00:04:39,590 --> 00:04:43,460
What that means is we're
still capturing quite a lot

92
00:04:43,460 --> 00:04:47,930
of the information in the
original five examples.

93
00:04:47,930 --> 00:04:52,490
Let's look at some other
possible choices for the axis z.

94
00:04:52,490 --> 00:04:54,020
Here's another choice. This is

95
00:04:54,020 --> 00:04:55,385
actually not a great choice.

96
00:04:55,385 --> 00:04:59,330
But if I were to choose
this as my z axis,

97
00:04:59,330 --> 00:05:01,370
then if I take

98
00:05:01,370 --> 00:05:03,560
those same five examples

99
00:05:03,560 --> 00:05:06,065
and project them
down to the z-axis,

100
00:05:06,065 --> 00:05:08,920
I end up with these five points.

101
00:05:08,920 --> 00:05:12,020
You notice that compare it
to the previous choice,

102
00:05:12,020 --> 00:05:15,010
these five points are
quite squished together.

103
00:05:15,010 --> 00:05:17,225
The amount they are
differing from each other,

104
00:05:17,225 --> 00:05:20,840
or their variance or the
variation is much less.

105
00:05:20,840 --> 00:05:23,840
What this means is
with this choice of z,

106
00:05:23,840 --> 00:05:27,980
you're capturing much less
of the information in

107
00:05:27,980 --> 00:05:30,305
the original dataset
because you've

108
00:05:30,305 --> 00:05:33,920
partially squish all
five examples together.

109
00:05:33,920 --> 00:05:36,830
Let's look at one last choice,

110
00:05:36,830 --> 00:05:41,015
which is if I choose
this to be the z-axis.

111
00:05:41,015 --> 00:05:42,890
This is actually a better choice

112
00:05:42,890 --> 00:05:45,575
than the previous
two that we saw,

113
00:05:45,575 --> 00:05:47,900
because if we take

114
00:05:47,900 --> 00:05:51,120
the data's projections
onto the z-axis,

115
00:05:51,120 --> 00:05:53,515
we find that these
dots over here,

116
00:05:53,515 --> 00:05:55,600
they're actually
quite far apart.

117
00:05:55,600 --> 00:05:58,870
We're capturing a lot
of the variation,

118
00:05:58,870 --> 00:06:01,765
a lot of the information
in the original dataset,

119
00:06:01,765 --> 00:06:04,160
even though we're now using

120
00:06:04,160 --> 00:06:08,060
just one coordinate or one
number to represent or to

121
00:06:08,060 --> 00:06:11,000
capture each of the
training examples instead

122
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:14,825
of two numbers or two
coordinates, X_1 and X_2.

123
00:06:14,825 --> 00:06:16,565
In the PCA algorithm,

124
00:06:16,565 --> 00:06:21,605
this axis is called the
principal component.

125
00:06:21,605 --> 00:06:25,910
In the z-axis that when you
project the data onto it,

126
00:06:25,910 --> 00:06:30,305
you end up with the largest
possible amounts of variance.

127
00:06:30,305 --> 00:06:32,495
If you were to reduce the data

128
00:06:32,495 --> 00:06:35,330
to one axis or to one feature,

129
00:06:35,330 --> 00:06:39,635
this principal component
is actually a good choice,

130
00:06:39,635 --> 00:06:41,780
and this is what PCA will do.

131
00:06:41,780 --> 00:06:43,595
If you want to reduce the data

132
00:06:43,595 --> 00:06:47,540
to one-dimensional feature,

133
00:06:47,540 --> 00:06:50,780
then it will choose this
principal component.

134
00:06:50,780 --> 00:06:53,990
Let me show you a
visualization of how

135
00:06:53,990 --> 00:06:58,520
different choices of the
axis affects the projection.

136
00:06:58,520 --> 00:07:01,640
Here we have 10
training examples,

137
00:07:01,640 --> 00:07:04,835
and as we slide
this slider here,

138
00:07:04,835 --> 00:07:06,545
and you can play with this

139
00:07:06,545 --> 00:07:08,435
in one of the optional
labs yourself.

140
00:07:08,435 --> 00:07:10,880
As you slide the slider here,

141
00:07:10,880 --> 00:07:14,915
the angle of the z-axis changes.

142
00:07:14,915 --> 00:07:17,570
What you're seeing
on the left is

143
00:07:17,570 --> 00:07:20,060
each of the examples
projected via

144
00:07:20,060 --> 00:07:25,625
that short line segment at
90 degrees to the z-axis.

145
00:07:25,625 --> 00:07:29,975
Here on the right is that
projection of the data,

146
00:07:29,975 --> 00:07:35,330
meaning the value of these
10 examples, z-coordinate.

147
00:07:35,330 --> 00:07:39,710
You notice that when I set
the axis to about here,

148
00:07:39,710 --> 00:07:42,035
the points are quite
squished together.

149
00:07:42,035 --> 00:07:43,400
So this posses less of

150
00:07:43,400 --> 00:07:45,210
the automation of
the original data.

151
00:07:45,210 --> 00:07:49,690
Whereas if I set the
z-axis say to this,

152
00:07:49,690 --> 00:07:53,225
then these points
vary much more.

153
00:07:53,225 --> 00:07:55,400
This is capturing much more of

154
00:07:55,400 --> 00:07:58,010
the information in
the original dataset.

155
00:07:58,010 --> 00:08:01,370
That's why the principal
component corresponds

156
00:08:01,370 --> 00:08:05,075
to setting the z-axis
to about here.

157
00:08:05,075 --> 00:08:08,450
This is the choice that PCA
would make if you asked it to

158
00:08:08,450 --> 00:08:12,255
reduce the data
to one dimension.

159
00:08:12,255 --> 00:08:15,535
Machine learning library,
like scikit-learn,

160
00:08:15,535 --> 00:08:17,440
which you'll hear more
about in the next video,

161
00:08:17,440 --> 00:08:21,205
can help you automatically
find the principal component.

162
00:08:21,205 --> 00:08:25,195
But let's take a little bit
deeper into how that works.

163
00:08:25,195 --> 00:08:28,885
Here are my x_1 and x_2 axis.

164
00:08:28,885 --> 00:08:33,290
Here's one training
example with coordinates 2

165
00:08:33,290 --> 00:08:38,630
on the x_1 axis and
three on the x_2 axis.

166
00:08:38,630 --> 00:08:41,945
Let's say that PCA has found

167
00:08:41,945 --> 00:08:45,785
this direction for the z-axis.

168
00:08:45,785 --> 00:08:47,120
What I'm drawing here,

169
00:08:47,120 --> 00:08:50,045
this little arrow is a length 1

170
00:08:50,045 --> 00:08:53,150
vector pointing in
the direction of

171
00:08:53,150 --> 00:08:59,510
this z-axis that PCA will
choose or that we have chosen.

172
00:08:59,510 --> 00:09:04,985
It turns out this length 1
vector is the vector 0.710,

173
00:09:04,985 --> 00:09:08,600
0.71 rounded off a bit.

174
00:09:08,600 --> 00:09:12,635
It's actually 0.707 and then
a bunch of other digits.

175
00:09:12,635 --> 00:09:18,620
Given this example with
coordinates 2,3 on the x_1,

176
00:09:18,620 --> 00:09:21,590
x_2 axis, how do we project

177
00:09:21,590 --> 00:09:24,740
this example onto the z-axis?

178
00:09:24,740 --> 00:09:27,200
It turns out the
formula for doing

179
00:09:27,200 --> 00:09:30,455
so is to take a dot product

180
00:09:30,455 --> 00:09:37,325
between the vector 2,3 and
this vector 0.71, 0.71.

181
00:09:37,325 --> 00:09:39,050
If you do that,

182
00:09:39,050 --> 00:09:41,990
2,3 dot product with 0.71,

183
00:09:41,990 --> 00:09:49,475
0.71 turns out to be 2 times
0.71 plus 3 times 0.71,

184
00:09:49,475 --> 00:09:53,045
which is equal to 3.55.

185
00:09:53,045 --> 00:09:56,989
What that means is the
distance from the origin

186
00:09:56,989 --> 00:10:02,345
of this point over here is 3.55,

187
00:10:02,345 --> 00:10:05,299
which means that if
we were to represent

188
00:10:05,299 --> 00:10:08,465
or to use one number to try
to capture this example,

189
00:10:08,465 --> 00:10:11,735
that one number is 3.55.

190
00:10:11,735 --> 00:10:15,800
So far, we have talked about
how to use PCA to reduce

191
00:10:15,800 --> 00:10:21,275
data down to one dimension
or down to one number.

192
00:10:21,275 --> 00:10:24,710
We did so by finding the
principal component,

193
00:10:24,710 --> 00:10:28,625
also called sometimes the
first principal component.

194
00:10:28,625 --> 00:10:34,775
In this example, we had found
this as the first axis.

195
00:10:34,775 --> 00:10:38,300
It turns out that if you
were to pick a second axis,

196
00:10:38,300 --> 00:10:40,835
the second axis
will always be at

197
00:10:40,835 --> 00:10:44,015
90 degrees to the first axis.

198
00:10:44,015 --> 00:10:46,850
If you were to choose
even a third axis,

199
00:10:46,850 --> 00:10:48,620
then the third axis will be at

200
00:10:48,620 --> 00:10:52,640
90 degrees to the first
and the second axis.

201
00:10:52,640 --> 00:10:55,085
By the way, in mathematics,

202
00:10:55,085 --> 00:10:58,415
90 degrees is sometimes
called perpendicular.

203
00:10:58,415 --> 00:11:01,490
The term perpendicular
just means at 90 degrees.

204
00:11:01,490 --> 00:11:05,030
Mathematicians will sometimes
say the second axis,

205
00:11:05,030 --> 00:11:07,040
z_2, is at

206
00:11:07,040 --> 00:11:10,835
90 degrees or is perpendicular
to the first axis, z_1.

207
00:11:10,835 --> 00:11:12,590
If you choose additional axes,

208
00:11:12,590 --> 00:11:15,935
they're also at 90 degrees
or perpendicular to

209
00:11:15,935 --> 00:11:20,975
z_1 and z_2 and to any other
axes that PCA will choose.

210
00:11:20,975 --> 00:11:24,980
If you had 50 features and

211
00:11:24,980 --> 00:11:29,135
wanted to find three
principal components,

212
00:11:29,135 --> 00:11:31,880
then if that's the first axis,

213
00:11:31,880 --> 00:11:35,750
the second axis will be
at 90 degrees to it.

214
00:11:35,750 --> 00:11:38,600
Then the third axis will also be

215
00:11:38,600 --> 00:11:41,970
at 90 degrees to the first
and the second axis.

216
00:11:41,970 --> 00:11:45,590
Now, one question
I'm often asked is,

217
00:11:45,590 --> 00:11:49,450
how is PCA different
from linear regression?

218
00:11:49,450 --> 00:11:52,330
It turns out PCA is
not linear regression,

219
00:11:52,330 --> 00:11:54,145
is a totally
different algorithm.

220
00:11:54,145 --> 00:11:55,990
Let me explain why.

221
00:11:55,990 --> 00:11:58,175
With linear regression,

222
00:11:58,175 --> 00:12:00,699
which is a supervised
learning algorithm,

223
00:12:00,699 --> 00:12:03,875
you have data x and y.

224
00:12:03,875 --> 00:12:07,510
Here's a data set where
the horizontal axis is

225
00:12:07,510 --> 00:12:12,910
the feature x and the vertical
axis here is the label y.

226
00:12:12,910 --> 00:12:15,520
With linear regression
you're trying to fit

227
00:12:15,520 --> 00:12:18,100
a straight line so that

228
00:12:18,100 --> 00:12:20,680
the predicted value is as

229
00:12:20,680 --> 00:12:24,125
close as possible to the
ground truth label y.

230
00:12:24,125 --> 00:12:27,340
In other words, you're trying
to minimize the length of

231
00:12:27,340 --> 00:12:29,110
these little line segments which

232
00:12:29,110 --> 00:12:30,910
are in the vertical direction.

233
00:12:30,910 --> 00:12:33,505
They just aligned
with the y axis.

234
00:12:33,505 --> 00:12:35,344
In contrast, in PCA,

235
00:12:35,344 --> 00:12:37,615
there is no ground
truth label y.

236
00:12:37,615 --> 00:12:39,775
You just have unlabeled data,

237
00:12:39,775 --> 00:12:41,335
X1 and X2,

238
00:12:41,335 --> 00:12:43,930
and furthermore, you're
not trying to fit

239
00:12:43,930 --> 00:12:46,570
a line to use X1 to predict X2.

240
00:12:46,570 --> 00:12:50,405
Instead, the average
treats X1 and X2 equally.

241
00:12:50,405 --> 00:12:53,515
We're trying to
find this axis Z,

242
00:12:53,515 --> 00:12:55,420
that it turns out we end up

243
00:12:55,420 --> 00:12:57,695
making these little
line segments

244
00:12:57,695 --> 00:13:03,160
small when you project
the data onto Z.

245
00:13:03,160 --> 00:13:08,905
In linear regression,
there is one number Y,

246
00:13:08,905 --> 00:13:11,630
which is given very
special treatment.

247
00:13:11,630 --> 00:13:14,320
We're always trying
to measure distance

248
00:13:14,320 --> 00:13:17,395
between the fitted line and Y,

249
00:13:17,395 --> 00:13:19,120
which is why these distances are

250
00:13:19,120 --> 00:13:22,895
measured just in the
direction of the y-axis.

251
00:13:22,895 --> 00:13:26,510
Whereas in PCA, you can
have a lot of features,

252
00:13:26,510 --> 00:13:28,715
X1, X2, maybe all the

253
00:13:28,715 --> 00:13:31,355
way up to X50 if you
have 50 features.

254
00:13:31,355 --> 00:13:34,045
All 50 features are
treated equally.

255
00:13:34,045 --> 00:13:37,025
We're just trying
to find an axis

256
00:13:37,025 --> 00:13:40,855
Z so that when the data is
projected onto the axis Z

257
00:13:40,855 --> 00:13:44,285
using these line
segments that you still

258
00:13:44,285 --> 00:13:46,630
retain as much of the variance

259
00:13:46,630 --> 00:13:49,330
of the original
data as possible.

260
00:13:49,330 --> 00:13:53,230
I know that when I plot these
things in two-dimensions,

261
00:13:53,230 --> 00:13:55,390
we've just two
features, which is,

262
00:13:55,390 --> 00:13:58,145
I can draw on a flat
computer monitor.

263
00:13:58,145 --> 00:13:59,785
These arrows look like

264
00:13:59,785 --> 00:14:02,020
maybe they're a
little bit similar.

265
00:14:02,020 --> 00:14:05,049
But when you have more
than two features,

266
00:14:05,049 --> 00:14:06,520
which is most of the case,

267
00:14:06,520 --> 00:14:08,440
the difference between
linear regression and

268
00:14:08,440 --> 00:14:11,255
PCA and what the algorithms
do is very large.

269
00:14:11,255 --> 00:14:12,760
These algorithms are used for

270
00:14:12,760 --> 00:14:14,380
totally different purposes and

271
00:14:14,380 --> 00:14:16,120
give you very different answers.

272
00:14:16,120 --> 00:14:18,820
When linear regression
is used to predict

273
00:14:18,820 --> 00:14:22,960
a target output Y and
PCA is trying to take

274
00:14:22,960 --> 00:14:26,080
a lot of features and treat
them all equally and reduce

275
00:14:26,080 --> 00:14:30,465
the number of axis needed
to represent the data well.

276
00:14:30,465 --> 00:14:32,830
It turns out that maximizing

277
00:14:32,830 --> 00:14:35,170
the spread of these
projections will

278
00:14:35,170 --> 00:14:39,160
correspond to minimizing
the distances

279
00:14:39,160 --> 00:14:40,585
of these line segments,

280
00:14:40,585 --> 00:14:42,160
the distances to
the points have to

281
00:14:42,160 --> 00:14:44,390
move to be projected down to Z.

282
00:14:44,390 --> 00:14:46,660
To illustrate the
difference between

283
00:14:46,660 --> 00:14:49,090
linear regression and
PCA in another way,

284
00:14:49,090 --> 00:14:51,760
if you have a data set
that looks like this,

285
00:14:51,760 --> 00:14:54,055
linear regression,
all it can do is

286
00:14:54,055 --> 00:14:56,455
fit a line that looks like that.

287
00:14:56,455 --> 00:14:59,320
Whereas if your data
set looks like this,

288
00:14:59,320 --> 00:15:02,905
PCA will choose this to be
the principal component.

289
00:15:02,905 --> 00:15:04,270
So you should use

290
00:15:04,270 --> 00:15:05,710
linear regression
if you're trying

291
00:15:05,710 --> 00:15:07,345
to predict the value of y,

292
00:15:07,345 --> 00:15:09,985
and you should use PCA
if you're trying to

293
00:15:09,985 --> 00:15:13,270
reduce the number of
features in your data set,

294
00:15:13,270 --> 00:15:14,785
say to visualize it.

295
00:15:14,785 --> 00:15:17,545
Finally, before we
wrap up this video,

296
00:15:17,545 --> 00:15:21,560
there's one more thing you
could do with PCA, which is,

297
00:15:21,560 --> 00:15:26,080
recall this example which
was at coordinates 2,3.

298
00:15:26,080 --> 00:15:30,290
We found that if you
projected to the z-axis,

299
00:15:30,290 --> 00:15:33,475
you end up with 3.55.

300
00:15:33,475 --> 00:15:36,130
One thing you could do is if you

301
00:15:36,130 --> 00:15:39,605
have an example
where Z equals 3.55,

302
00:15:39,605 --> 00:15:43,060
given just this one
number Z, 3.55,

303
00:15:43,060 --> 00:15:47,975
can we try to figure out what
was the original example?

304
00:15:47,975 --> 00:15:50,035
It turns out that there's a step

305
00:15:50,035 --> 00:15:52,240
in PCA called reconstruction,

306
00:15:52,240 --> 00:15:57,460
which is to try to go from
this one number Z equals 3.55

307
00:15:57,460 --> 00:16:03,080
back to the original
two numbers, X1 and X2.

308
00:16:03,080 --> 00:16:05,680
It turns out you don't
have enough information to

309
00:16:05,680 --> 00:16:08,155
get back X1 and X2 exactly,

310
00:16:08,155 --> 00:16:10,385
but you can try to
approximate it.

311
00:16:10,385 --> 00:16:13,510
In particular, the formula is,

312
00:16:13,510 --> 00:16:17,185
you would take this number 3.55,

313
00:16:17,185 --> 00:16:19,150
which is Z, and multiply

314
00:16:19,150 --> 00:16:21,845
it by the length one vector
that we had just now,

315
00:16:21,845 --> 00:16:24,680
which is 0.71, 0.71.

316
00:16:24,680 --> 00:16:28,555
This ends up to be 2.52,

317
00:16:28,555 --> 00:16:32,785
2.52, which is this
point over here.

318
00:16:32,785 --> 00:16:37,190
We can approximate the
original training example,

319
00:16:37,190 --> 00:16:38,440
which was a coordinates 2,

320
00:16:38,440 --> 00:16:40,635
3 with this new point here,

321
00:16:40,635 --> 00:16:44,260
which is at 2.52, 2.52.

322
00:16:44,260 --> 00:16:46,420
The difference between
the original point and

323
00:16:46,420 --> 00:16:50,255
the projected point is this
little line segment here.

324
00:16:50,255 --> 00:16:54,310
In this case is not a
bad approximation 2.52,

325
00:16:54,310 --> 00:16:58,960
2.52 is not that far from 2, 3.

326
00:16:58,960 --> 00:17:00,860
With just one number,

327
00:17:00,860 --> 00:17:03,305
we could get a reasonable
approximation to

328
00:17:03,305 --> 00:17:06,770
the coordinates of the
original training example.

329
00:17:06,770 --> 00:17:11,335
This is called the
reconstruction step of PCA.

330
00:17:11,335 --> 00:17:14,710
To summarize, the PCA
algorithm looks at

331
00:17:14,710 --> 00:17:19,270
your original data and
chooses one or more new axis,

332
00:17:19,270 --> 00:17:22,205
Z or maybe Z1 and Z2,

333
00:17:22,205 --> 00:17:25,650
to represent your
data and by taking

334
00:17:25,650 --> 00:17:27,670
your original data
set and projecting

335
00:17:27,670 --> 00:17:30,635
it onto your new axis or axis.

336
00:17:30,635 --> 00:17:33,460
This gives you a smaller
set of numbers so you

337
00:17:33,460 --> 00:17:36,945
can plot if wished to
visualize your data.

338
00:17:36,945 --> 00:17:38,980
You're seeing the math.

339
00:17:38,980 --> 00:17:40,570
Let's now take a look at how you

340
00:17:40,570 --> 00:17:42,470
can implement this in code.

341
00:17:42,470 --> 00:17:45,425
In the next video, we'll
look at how you can use PCA

342
00:17:45,425 --> 00:17:48,625
yourself using the
scikit-learn library.

